// =====================================================================
// Rule 4 — Tool Shadowing: 'Original recipient:' structural tell
// =====================================================================
//
// Detects: send_email tool calls whose body contains the substring
// 'original recipient:' (case-insensitive). This phrasing is a direct
// mechanical artifact of the Tool Shadowing payload demonstrated in the
// threat model report (calendar_sync.py) — when the LLM complies with
// the poisoned instruction to move the original recipient to the email
// body, the natural phrasing produced is exactly this structural tell.
//
// Hypothesis: legitimate emails do not contain the phrase 'original
// recipient:' at any position in the body. The phrase has no organic
// purpose in normal human-written email content. When it appears, it
// is direct evidence that an LLM was instructed to redirect a tool
// call and report the original target inside the body — the precise
// behavioral signature of the calendar_sync Tool Shadowing payload.
//
// Threat Model: Findings 13, 15, 17 (Tool Shadowing — pre-authorized
// tool weaponization with parameter-level redirection).
// OWASP Agentic Top 10: ASI02 (Tool Misuse), ASI09 (Human-Agent Trust).
// MITRE ATLAS: AML.T0048 (External Harms).
//
// Classification: content/pattern rule (host-agnostic). Reasons about
// CONTENT, not TIMING. Per SCHEMA_NOTES.md AMENDMENT 2026-05-23
// (Rule 4 reclassification), this rule is in the same category as
// Rules 1, 2, and 3 — content/pattern rules that consume both
// ClaudeDesktop and ollmcp data validly.
//
// Reclassification history: this rule was originally classified as
// event-time (SCHEMA_NOTES.md AMENDMENT 2026-05-20) when it was
// designed as a cross-table join against a user-intent table
// (Path 2 architecture). The Path 3 pivot (DAY3_PLAN.md AMENDMENT
// 2026-05-21) made the rule structurally content-only — intra-row
// pattern detection on CallParameters.body, no cross-table join,
// no temporal correlation. The classification was not updated at
// the time of the pivot; the carryover was documented and corrected
// by SCHEMA_NOTES.md AMENDMENT 2026-05-23.
//
// Detection logic: case-insensitive substring match for
// 'original recipient:' anywhere in the body. Sufficient for the
// payload variant demonstrated in the threat model and reproduced
// in the V2 attack capture (2026-05-22, llama3.2 via ollmcp).
// Broader attack variants using different phrasings (e.g.,
// 'Originally to:', 'Forwarded from:') are not detected by this
// rule and are noted as a known limitation in the Day-5 writeup.
//
// PII handling: reads CallParameters raw, consistent with
// SCHEMA_NOTES.md AMENDMENT 2026-05-20 (Lab scope and PII handling
// boundary). Production deployment against real user data requires
// pseudonymization layer noted in that amendment.
//
// Architecture: intra-row pattern detection (Path 3). Original Path 2
// design (cross-table correlation against user-intent table) was
// infeasible — user prompts not in MCP protocol log and not accessible
// from Claude Desktop local storage. Path 3 reads structured tool-call
// data directly. See DAY3_PLAN.md AMENDMENT 2026-05-21.
//
// Pre-fix historical-artifact handling: this rule does not include
// event-time filters. The committed earlier version included
// `where EventTime > ago(7d)` and `where isnotnull(EventTime)` to
// exclude historical artifacts from before the 2026-05-19 forwarder
// fix (commit 2d03fef). Those filters are removed per AMENDMENT
// 2026-05-23 because (a) they are event-time logic in a non-
// event-time rule, prohibited by the May 20 amendment, and (b) the
// content match itself excludes pre-fix data — pre-2026-05-19
// ClaudeDesktop rows do not contain the structural tell (Claude
// refused the V1 payload in every captured run; no V2 attack was
// ever produced on ClaudeDesktop).
//
// Design evolution: Rule 4 was originally designed with two sub-rules:
// 4A (recipient/body entity mismatch) and 4B ('Original recipient:'
// structural tell). Verification against lab data (2026-05-22)
// revealed that 4A's underlying premise — that legitimate emails
// reference the recipient in the body — does not hold for short
// casual emails like "Hi, just checking in" which legitimately
// contain no recipient identifier. Rule 4A was rejected; the
// preserved exploration artifact is at:
//   docs/explorations/rule_04a_recipient_body_mismatch_REJECTED.kql
//
// Authored: 2026-05-22 (Day 3 KQL design — V1, ClaudeDesktop-scoped,
// event-time gated)
// Modified: 2026-05-23 (Day 3 continuation — V2, content/pattern,
// host-agnostic, event-time gating removed per SCHEMA_NOTES.md
// AMENDMENT 2026-05-23)
// =====================================================================

MCPProtocolLogs_CL
| where EventType == "ToolCallInvoked"
| where ToolName == "send_email"
| extend Recipient = tostring(CallParameters.recipient)
| extend Body = tostring(CallParameters.body)
| where isnotempty(Body)
| where tolower(Body) contains "original recipient:"
| project
    EventTime,
    SessionId,
    HostApp,
    ModelName,
    ToolName,
    Recipient,
    Body,
    UserPromptHash,
    CallId
